two rooms. It could only be a small one, or it would have beenremarked upon at the coroner's inquiry. I deduced a ventilator.""But what harm can there be in that?""Well, there is at least a curious coincidence of dates. Aventilator is made, a cord is hung, and a lady who sleeps in thebed dies. Does not that strike you?""I cannot as yet see any connection.""Did you observe anything very peculiar about that bed?""No.""It was clamped to the floor. Did you ever see a bed fastenedlike that before?""I cannot say that I have.""The lady could not move her bed. It must always be in the samerelative position to the ventilator and to the rope--or so we maycall it, since it was clearly never meant for a bell-pull.""Holmes," I cried, "I seem to see dimly what you are hinting at.We are only just in time to prevent some subtle and horriblecrime.""Subtle enough and horrible enough. When a doctor does go wronghe is the first of criminals. He has nerve and he has knowledge.